        {
            "author_info": {
                "name": "Andrew Weill",
                "href": "/profile/Andrew-Weill"
            },
            "answer_text": "My former partner did, and he wasn\u2019t the only one. In the US, at least, the undergraduate major isn\u2019t all that important. I think what\u2019s much more important is that the major is demanding, requiring lots of analytical reading, composition, and participation. It should necessitate careful time management and be recognized as a high quality program. And ideally the student will have handled all these demands, reflected by grades, recommendations, and work product. That\u2019s going to show law school readiness, regardless of whether the major is math, philosophy, art history, French literature, or biochemistry. ",
